7 A sweet breeze, without
8 having any change in itself, struck my forehead
9 no more sharply than a gentle wind;

10 because of which the leaves, trembling, all
11 of them leaned toward the side
12 where the holy mountain casts its first shadow;

13 not however from their being straight parted
14 so much, that the little birds on the tops
15 ceased to practice every art of theirs;

22 My slow steps had already carried me
23 so far into the ancient forest that I
24 could not see again where I had entered;

34 I stopped with my feet and with my eyes I crossed
35 beyond the little river, to gaze at
36 the great variety of the fresh shrubs;

55 she turned toward me over the red and yellow
56 flowers, in the same way
57 that a maiden lowers her modest eyes;

70 The river kept us three paces apart;
71 but the Hellespont, where Xerxes crossed,
72 still a check to all human arrogance,

79 some suspicion keeps you wondering;
80 but the psalm Delectasti sheds light,
81 which can clear your understanding.

94 Through his own fault he lived here a short time;
95 through his own fault he exchanged honorable laughter and sweet play
96 for weeping and suffering.

106 at this height, which is completely dissolved
107 in the living air, such motion strikes it,
108 and makes the forest rustle because it is dense;

109 and the struck plant has so much power
110 that it impregnates the air with its virtue,
111 and that air, in turn, shakes everything around as it circulates;

121 The water that you see does not rise from a spring
122 that replenishes vapor that frost converts,
123 like a river that gains and loses strength;

127 From this side it descends with the power
128 that takes away the memory of sin from others;
129 from the other side it restores the memory of every good deed.

136 I will give you one more corollary as a favor;
137 and I do not think that my words will be less dear to you,
138 if I go beyond my promise in speaking with you.

